420","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","about 1389":"about 1389","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1417":"1417","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Battle, Sussex, England":"Battle, Sussex, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fryer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Freer   1.","Americanized form of German   Freier   or   Freyer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Freer","meanings":["English: sometimes from Middle English <i>frere</i>, <i>frier</i> ‘brother, friend, comrade’ (Old French <i>frere</i>). During the 13th century, however, the word increasingly denoted ‘member of one of the mendicant religious orders’, the usual modern sense of the word <i>friar</i>. The first friars arrived in England in 1224. As with   Abbot  ,   Monk  ,   Nunn  , and   Prior  , late medieval use of <i>Frere</i> as a nickname was probably uncomplimentary, for by the mid 14th century the once popular friars had become a byword in satirical literature for self-indulgent, smooth-talking hypocrisy. Friars were not allowed to marry, but some of them probably fathered children. After the Reformation former friars were free to marry, and one such is said to have been the progenitor of the Friers of Melrose parish, Roxburgh, an instance, if true, of post-medieval surname creation. The name may also be occupational, for someone who lived or worked at a friary (Middle English <i>frere</i> ‘house of friars’).","Americanized form of French <b>Frère</b> (see   Frere  ).","German: cognate of   Friedrich  ."]}]},{"name":"Joane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, and so a doublet of   Joan .  This too was revived as a given name in its own right in the first half of the 20th century. It has to some extent been influenced by the independently formed combination <i>Jo Anne</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Johanne","meanings":["and Norwegian feminine form of   Johan ."]},{"name":"Joann","meanings":["From Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, and so a doublet of   Joan .  This too was revived as a given name in its own right in the first half of the 20th century. It has to some extent been influenced by the independently formed combination <i>Jo Anne</i>."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Joane Fryer was born in 1375, in Battle, Sussex, England. She married John Baker VII about 1389, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1417, in England, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1375–1417":"1375–1417","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","about 1389":"umbes 1389","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1417":"1417","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Battle, Sussex, England":"Battle, Sussex, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"1375–1417":"1375–1417","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","about 1389":"noin 1389","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1417":"1417","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Battle, Sussex, England":"Battle, Sussex, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fr":{"1375–141